<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-580-529  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 580 529.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  Nov 5 1990 v219 n20 p30(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Pacific Bell expects big things from small packages. (digital loopcarrier systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Maciel, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The next generation of digital loop carrier (DLC) systems mustincorporate greater capabilities packaged in small, versatilemodules.andP;  Development of such DLC systems is fundamental inPacific Bell's plans for transitioning to an all-digital,all-fiber subscriber loop network.andP;  Pacific Bell envisions DLCsystems functioning as software-controlled customer service nodes(CSNs) in the local loop network.andP;  The telco plans to deploy suchCSNs throughout the subscriber loop network.andP;  Over the long term,Pacific Bell expects that use of very large scale integration(VLSI) technologies will reduce component sizes.andP;  Small modularcomponents will make upgrades possible without major backplane orequipment changes.andP;  Pacific Bell's strategic planners foreseediminished costs for CSN systems, saying that modular designs andadherence to generic standards will help in controlling costs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Pacific Bell (Planning).andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesDigital communicationsMiniaturizationFiber opticsTelephone systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Glossary. (table)Customer service node functional drawing. (chart)Typical customer service node architecture. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>